snippet.title: Demon Snatchers
snippet.description: Pilot season is around the corner, and word on the street is "Ghost Punchers" got picked up for a full season before the first episode aired. The "Demon Snatchers" crew will have to go big for sweeps, or go home. Either way, apparently their neighbor is having a barbecue, so there's always that to look forward to.

snippet.title: Bro Breakup
snippet.description: Memories came flooding up, of the moments spent adrift in the grasp of his sweet bro as they slammed a monster hi-five, or the epic NCAA-style beer pong championship trophy ceremony they shared. His only hope was that the platonic love of his life felt the same way right now, and as if by magic, his wishes came true. Never again would they let a Girls Gone Wild DVD come between them.

snippet.title: Ben's Head Revisited
snippet.description: It's his brain capacity, coupled with his ability to stay calm under pressure, that makes him a merciless opponent in "Scene It: Harry Potter Edition" tournaments.

snippet.title: Wrong Answer
snippet.description: To be fair, how can you live in this cruel world when you find out Falkor the Luck Dragon from "The Neverending Story" isn't real? It's like discovering Santa Claus doesn't exist, except 1,000 times worse because it's Falkor the Luck Dragon.

snippet.title: Mondays on CBS
snippet.description: The station managers didn't even broadcast the first five minutes in English, and whoever edited the pilot accidentally put in footage of their pet parakeet dying in front of a fireplace. It still scored a 14.1, beating Parks and Recreation by 14.06 points. The coveted "Dying/Unsure of How to Program the Remote" demo remained The Eye's once again.

snippet.title: 5secondfilms Week In Review #170
snippet.description: After winning a raffle for the prized Kelsey Cat, the winning man's old habits for over analyzing Reggae lyricism while high climaxes into a petty argument about who really shot the Sheriff in that Bob Marley song with his new dumb cat.

snippet.title: Assassination Attempt
snippet.description: Sheriff Brimley Spiggensbottom couldn't read, but he could understand sign language. It was only a matter of time before his customized hand bible turned on him -- and with election time coming up so soon, too.

snippet.title: Petty Argument
snippet.description: His therapist isn't much help either. Just a lot of screaming and cowering behind bookshelves, with all those fancy books he read in his fancy-schmancy therapist school. Bet they don't have a chapter on how to deal with giant feelings.

snippet.title: Old Habits
snippet.description: Would that he could gallop back to those halcyon days, when sunlight streamed in through the haylofts and wood dust swirled in the moonbeams and everything was right with the world. Alas, his mother Strider needed money to keep the farm going and the town would turn on them both if they knew a female horse was made to run a farm in secret for years. His burden was ample but his heart was true.

snippet.title: Kelsey Cat
snippet.description: On a morning when she's feeling a little too "urpy," she'll saunter over to a bowl of Sambuca, drink it, then barf up whatever organic kale she had the night before. Then she scratches your door until you clean it up. One must earn Kelsey Cat's affections.

Meanwhile, an inconspicuous tan Chevy sped off into the marshland, eventually climbing higher and higher into the sky and disappearing with a twinkly flourish. Only the children noticed, as children often do. But alas, it was not enough evidence for the prosecution to push for Murder 1.
